======================================================================
THE PIGEONHOLE ARGUMENT
======================================================================

At n=6, there are C(6,3)/2 = 10 complementary pairs of 3-sets.
CLAIM: If a tournament has c3 >= 8 3-cycle vertex sets,
then some complementary pair are both 3-cycles, giving alpha_2 >= 1.

Min complementary cycle pairs by c3 (3-cycle vertex set count), n=6:
  c3= 0: min comp pairs = 0, range [0, 0]
  c3= 1: min comp pairs = 0, range [0, 0]
  c3= 2: min comp pairs = 0, range [0, 0]
  c3= 3: min comp pairs = 0, range [0, 0]
  c3= 4: min comp pairs = 0, range [0, 0]
  c3= 5: min comp pairs = 0, range [0, 0]
  c3= 6: min comp pairs = 0, range [0, 0]
  c3= 7: min comp pairs = 0, range [0, 0]
  c3= 8: min comp pairs = 0, range [0, 0]

======================================================================
THE VERTEX-COVER ARGUMENT FOR alpha_1=10
======================================================================

Each 3-cycle uses 3 of 6 vertices. Each vertex appears in C(5,2)=10
of the C(6,3)=20 possible 3-vertex subsets.

If c3 3-vertex subsets are 3-cycles, then each of the 10 complementary
pairs (S, S^c) has probability roughly (c3/20)^2 of both being cycles.
Expected complementary cycle pairs ~ 10 * (c3/20)^2.

For alpha_1=10 with only 3-cycles (c5=0):
  c3=10 directed 3-cycles means c3=10 vertex sets are 3-cycles.
  Expected comp pairs ~ 10 * (10/20)^2 = 10/4 = 2.5
  MINIMUM comp pairs = ?


======================================================================
COMBINATORIAL LOWER BOUND ON COMPLEMENTARY PAIRS
======================================================================

Model: 20 3-vertex subsets of {0,...,5}, paired into 10 complementary pairs.
Choose c3 of the 20 subsets. How few complementary pairs can be hit?

  c3= 0: lower bound = max(0, 0-10) = 0, actual min = 0
  c3= 1: lower bound = max(0, 1-10) = 0, actual min = 0
  c3= 2: lower bound = max(0, 2-10) = 0, actual min = 0
  c3= 3: lower bound = max(0, 3-10) = 0, actual min = 0
  c3= 4: lower bound = max(0, 4-10) = 0, actual min = 0
  c3= 5: lower bound = max(0, 5-10) = 0, actual min = 0
  c3= 6: lower bound = max(0, 6-10) = 0, actual min = 0
  c3= 7: lower bound = max(0, 7-10) = 0, actual min = 0
  c3= 8: lower bound = max(0, 8-10) = 0, actual min = 0
  c3= 9: lower bound = max(0, 9-10) = 0, actual min = ?
  c3=10: lower bound = max(0, 10-10) = 0, actual min = ?
  c3=11: lower bound = max(0, 11-10) = 1, actual min = ?
  c3=12: lower bound = max(0, 12-10) = 2, actual min = ?
  c3=13: lower bound = max(0, 13-10) = 3, actual min = ?
  c3=14: lower bound = max(0, 14-10) = 4, actual min = ?
  c3=15: lower bound = max(0, 15-10) = 5, actual min = ?
  c3=16: lower bound = max(0, 16-10) = 6, actual min = ?
  c3=17: lower bound = max(0, 17-10) = 7, actual min = ?
  c3=18: lower bound = max(0, 18-10) = 8, actual min = ?
  c3=19: lower bound = max(0, 19-10) = 9, actual min = ?
  c3=20: lower bound = max(0, 20-10) = 10, actual min = ?

KEY INSIGHT: the lower bound max(0, c3-10) comes from
the 10 complementary pairs being a PERFECT MATCHING on 20 items.
Any selection of c3 > 10 items from 20 must include both
endpoints of at least c3-10 matched pairs.

For alpha_1=10 with ONLY 3-cycles: c3=10 of the 20 subsets.
  => at least max(0, 10-10)=0 complementary pairs FORCED.
  But the ACTUAL minimum is higher because tournament structure constrains
  which 10 of the 20 subsets can be 3-cycles.

CRITICAL: Tournament structure prevents choosing an independent set!
The achievable 3-cycle configurations are NOT arbitrary subsets.
Regular tournament at n=5 (unique): c3=2, so 3-cycle vertex sets
are highly constrained by the tournament orientation.

